crates' home. Archidamus is written in the voice of the Spartan prince to his assembly, and Plataicus is in the voice of a citizen of Plataea asking Athens for aid, while in To Philip, Isocrates himself calls on Philip of Macedon to lead a unified Greece against Persia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., GreekvTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aGagarin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMirhady, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapillon, Terry L.1 aPapillon, Terry L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToo, Yun Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70245540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797376423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797376/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK